    <id>https://doi.org/10.1177/10422587251401186</id>
    <title>Family Governance and Home Country’s Family Collectivism in Internationalization: A Meta-Analysis of Family Firm Heterogeneity</title>
    <updated>2026-01-17T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Ilaria Gallegati, Antonio Majocchi, Florian B. Zapkau</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Entrepreneurship Theory and Practice&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Family firms are not a homogeneous group. Thus, we theorize and empirically validate how governance differences among family firms (family governance heterogeneity) influence internationalization, considering the home country’s level of family collectivism as a moderator. Drawing on the bifurcation bias approach, we conduct a multilevel meta-analysis on 33,493 family firms. Our findings suggest that family CEOs and greater family involvement on the board hamper internationalization, but family collectivism improves these relationships. In contrast, non-founding generations promote internationalization independently of this country-level moderator. Our study reconciles the theoretical and empirical inconsistencies in the relationship between family governance and family firm internationalization.</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1177/10422587251401186"/>
    <category term="Entrepreneurship Theory and Practice"/>
    <published>2026-01-17T00:00:00+00:00</published>
